Note:
==============================================================================
SQL - SQL AST (Statements, Expressions, Joins, Window) (Tier 1)
==============================================================================

Implements the SQL substrate per ISO/IEC 9075-2:2016 (Foundation), with
dialect-tagged extension points for PostgreSQL, MySQL, SQLite, Oracle,
SQL Server, BigQuery, Snowflake, Redshift, and Spark SQL.  The AST
covers the union of constructs found in those dialects' real-world
usage; per-dialect lowering is the responsibility of the serializer
(future work).

Statement kinds (SQL/Foundation 4.34, "Statements"):

  SQL_STMT_SELECT      1   SELECT statement
  SQL_STMT_INSERT      2   INSERT statement
  SQL_STMT_UPDATE      3   UPDATE statement
  SQL_STMT_DELETE      4   DELETE statement
  SQL_STMT_CREATE_TABLE   5
  SQL_STMT_ALTER_TABLE    6
  SQL_STMT_DROP_TABLE     7
  SQL_STMT_CREATE_INDEX   8
  SQL_STMT_CREATE_VIEW    9
  SQL_STMT_BEGIN          10
  SQL_STMT_COMMIT         11
  SQL_STMT_ROLLBACK       12
  SQL_STMT_GRANT          13
  SQL_STMT_REVOKE         14

Expression kinds:

  SQL_EXPR_COLUMN_REF       1
  SQL_EXPR_LITERAL          2
  SQL_EXPR_BINARY_OP        3
  SQL_EXPR_UNARY_OP         4
  SQL_EXPR_FUNCTION_CALL    5
  SQL_EXPR_CASE_WHEN        6
  SQL_EXPR_SUBQUERY         7
  SQL_EXPR_CAST             8
  SQL_EXPR_COLLATE          9
  SQL_EXPR_WINDOW_FUNCTION  10
  SQL_EXPR_AGGREGATE        11

Join kinds (SQL/Foundation 7.10):

  SQL_JOIN_INNER       1
  SQL_JOIN_LEFT_OUTER  2
  SQL_JOIN_RIGHT_OUTER 3
  SQL_JOIN_FULL_OUTER  4
  SQL_JOIN_CROSS       5
  SQL_JOIN_LATERAL     6

Dialect tags:

  SQL_DIALECT_STANDARD     0   ISO/IEC 9075 baseline
  SQL_DIALECT_POSTGRESQL   1
  SQL_DIALECT_MYSQL        2
  SQL_DIALECT_SQLITE       3
  SQL_DIALECT_ORACLE       4
  SQL_DIALECT_MSSQL        5
  SQL_DIALECT_BIGQUERY     6
  SQL_DIALECT_SNOWFLAKE    7
  SQL_DIALECT_REDSHIFT     8
  SQL_DIALECT_SPARK        9

Statement record layout (48 bytes):
  off  0  statement kind tag
  off  8  payload 0  (interpretation per kind)
  off 16  payload 1
  off 24  payload 2
  off 32  payload 3
  off 40  dialect tag

Expression record layout (48 bytes):
  off  0  expr kind tag
  off  8  payload 0
  off 16  payload 1
  off 24  payload 2
  off 32  payload 3
  off 40  reserved

SELECT statement payloads:
  payload 0: WITH clause (List of CTE records) or 0
  payload 1: select list (List of select-item records)
  payload 2: FROM/JOIN tree (List of join-spec records) or 0
  payload 3: pointer to "rest" record holding WHERE/GROUP/HAVING/WINDOW/
             ORDER/LIMIT/OFFSET fields (allocated only when used)
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_primitive.runa" as StringPrim
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TAG CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================

Constant SQL_STMT_SELECT as Integer is 1
Constant SQL_STMT_INSERT as Integer is 2
Constant SQL_STMT_UPDATE as Integer is 3
Constant SQL_STMT_DELETE as Integer is 4
Constant SQL_STMT_CREATE_TABLE as Integer is 5
Constant SQL_STMT_ALTER_TABLE as Integer is 6
Constant SQL_STMT_DROP_TABLE as Integer is 7
Constant SQL_STMT_CREATE_INDEX as Integer is 8
Constant SQL_STMT_CREATE_VIEW as Integer is 9
Constant SQL_STMT_BEGIN as Integer is 10
Constant SQL_STMT_COMMIT as Integer is 11
Constant SQL_STMT_ROLLBACK as Integer is 12
Constant SQL_STMT_GRANT as Integer is 13
Constant SQL_STMT_REVOKE as Integer is 14

Constant SQL_EXPR_COLUMN_REF as Integer is 1
Constant SQL_EXPR_LITERAL as Integer is 2
Constant SQL_EXPR_BINARY_OP as Integer is 3
Constant SQL_EXPR_UNARY_OP as Integer is 4
Constant SQL_EXPR_FUNCTION_CALL as Integer is 5
Constant SQL_EXPR_CASE_WHEN as Integer is 6
Constant SQL_EXPR_SUBQUERY as Integer is 7
Constant SQL_EXPR_CAST as Integer is 8
Constant SQL_EXPR_COLLATE as Integer is 9
Constant SQL_EXPR_WINDOW_FUNCTION as Integer is 10
Constant SQL_EXPR_AGGREGATE as Integer is 11

Constant SQL_JOIN_INNER as Integer is 1
Constant SQL_JOIN_LEFT_OUTER as Integer is 2
Constant SQL_JOIN_RIGHT_OUTER as Integer is 3
Constant SQL_JOIN_FULL_OUTER as Integer is 4
Constant SQL_JOIN_CROSS as Integer is 5
Constant SQL_JOIN_LATERAL as Integer is 6

Constant SQL_DIALECT_STANDARD as Integer is 0
Constant SQL_DIALECT_POSTGRESQL as Integer is 1
Constant SQL_DIALECT_MYSQL as Integer is 2
Constant SQL_DIALECT_SQLITE as Integer is 3
Constant SQL_DIALECT_ORACLE as Integer is 4
Constant SQL_DIALECT_MSSQL as Integer is 5
Constant SQL_DIALECT_BIGQUERY as Integer is 6
Constant SQL_DIALECT_SNOWFLAKE as Integer is 7
Constant SQL_DIALECT_REDSHIFT as Integer is 8
Constant SQL_DIALECT_SPARK as Integer is 9

Constant SQL_RECORD_SIZE as Integer is 48
Constant SQL_OFF_KIND as Integer is 0
Constant SQL_OFF_P0 as Integer is 8
Constant SQL_OFF_P1 as Integer is 16
Constant SQL_OFF_P2 as Integer is 24
Constant SQL_OFF_P3 as Integer is 32
Constant SQL_OFF_DIALECT as Integer is 40

Constant SQL_OK as Integer is 0
Constant SQL_NULL as Integer is -1

Note: Literal subtype tags (stored in payload 1 of SQL_EXPR_LITERAL).
Constant SQL_LIT_NULL as Integer is 0
Constant SQL_LIT_INTEGER as Integer is 1
Constant SQL_LIT_FLOAT as Integer is 2
Constant SQL_LIT_STRING as Integer is 3
Constant SQL_LIT_BOOLEAN as Integer is 4
Constant SQL_LIT_DATE as Integer is 5
Constant SQL_LIT_TIME as Integer is 6
Constant SQL_LIT_TIMESTAMP as Integer is 7
Constant SQL_LIT_INTERVAL as Integer is 8
Constant SQL_LIT_BLOB as Integer is 9

Note: Binary operator tags (stored in payload 0 of SQL_EXPR_BINARY_OP).
Constant SQL_OP_ADD as Integer is 1
Constant SQL_OP_SUB as Integer is 2
Constant SQL_OP_MUL as Integer is 3
Constant SQL_OP_DIV as Integer is 4
Constant SQL_OP_MOD as Integer is 5
Constant SQL_OP_CONCAT as Integer is 6
Constant SQL_OP_EQ as Integer is 7
Constant SQL_OP_NEQ as Integer is 8
Constant SQL_OP_LT as Integer is 9
Constant SQL_OP_LE as Integer is 10
Constant SQL_OP_GT as Integer is 11
Constant SQL_OP_GE as Integer is 12
Constant SQL_OP_AND as Integer is 13
Constant SQL_OP_OR as Integer is 14
Constant SQL_OP_LIKE as Integer is 15
Constant SQL_OP_IN as Integer is 16
Constant SQL_OP_IS as Integer is 17
Constant SQL_OP_IS_NOT as Integer is 18

Note: Unary operator tags.
Constant SQL_UOP_NEG as Integer is 1
Constant SQL_UOP_NOT as Integer is 2
Constant SQL_UOP_IS_NULL as Integer is 3
Constant SQL_UOP_IS_NOT_NULL as Integer is 4

Note: ============================================================================
Note: RECORD ALLOCATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Allocate a tagged 48-byte SQL record (used for both statements and
expressions; dialect slot is zero by default).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation
Layout.allocate(48); write the kind and four payload slots; zero
dialect.
@End Implementation
@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints
@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on OOM.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "sql_alloc" takes kind as Integer, p0 as Integer, p1 as Integer, p2 as Integer, p3 as Integer returns Integer:
    Let rec be proc allocate from Layout with SQL_RECORD_SIZE
    If rec is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rec, SQL_OFF_KIND, kind
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rec, SQL_OFF_P0, p0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rec, SQL_OFF_P1, p1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rec, SQL_OFF_P2, p2
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rec, SQL_OFF_P3, p3
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rec, SQL_OFF_DIALECT, 0
    Return rec
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: EXPRESSION CONSTRUCTORS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Construct a column-reference expression.  qualifier may be 0 (unqualified
column) or the owning table / alias name.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation
sql_alloc with SQL_EXPR_COLUMN_REF; p0 = qualifier, p1 = column name.
@End Implementation
@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints
@Security_Scope
Owned name strings.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "sql_column_ref" takes qualifier as Integer, column_name as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc sql_alloc with SQL_EXPR_COLUMN_REF, qualifier, column_name, 0, 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Construct a literal expression.  literal_kind is one of SQL_LIT_* and
text is the textual form (canonical SQL literal representation).  For
NULL literals, pass SQL_LIT_NULL and 0 for text.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation
sql_alloc with SQL_EXPR_LITERAL; p0 = text, p1 = literal_kind.
@End Implementation
@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints
@Security_Scope
Owned text string.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "sql_literal" takes text as Integer, literal_kind as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc sql_alloc with SQL_EXPR_LITERAL, text, literal_kind, 0, 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Binary operator expression per SQL/Foundation 6.27 ("Numeric value
expressions") and 8.x (comparison/logical predicates).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation
sql_alloc with SQL_EXPR_BINARY_OP; p0 = operator tag, p1 = LHS, p2 = RHS.
@End Implementation
@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints
@Security_Scope
Owns both operands.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "sql_binary_op" takes op as Integer, lhs as Integer, rhs as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc sql_alloc with SQL_EXPR_BINARY_OP, op, lhs, rhs, 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Unary operator expression.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation
sql_alloc with SQL_EXPR_UNARY_OP; p0 = uop tag, p1 = operand.
@End Implementation
@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints
@Security_Scope
Owns operand.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "sql_unary_op" takes uop as Integer, operand as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc sql_alloc with SQL_EXPR_UNARY_OP, uop, operand, 0, 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Function call expression per SQL/Foundation 6.x.  args is a List of
SQL expressions.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation
sql_alloc with SQL_EXPR_FUNCTION_CALL; p0 = name, p1 = args list,
p2 = distinct flag (0 or 1).
@End Implementation
@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints
@Security_Scope
Owns name and args list.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "sql_function_call" takes name as Integer, args as Integer, distinct as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc sql_alloc with SQL_EXPR_FUNCTION_CALL, name, args, distinct, 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Aggregate expression (COUNT, SUM, AVG, MIN, MAX, ...).  Modeled
separately from generic function call so optimizers can recognise
aggregates without name-matching.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation
sql_alloc with SQL_EXPR_AGGREGATE; p0 = name, p1 = args list,
p2 = distinct flag.
@End Implementation
@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints
@Security_Scope
Owns name and args list.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "sql_aggregate" takes name as Integer, args as Integer, distinct as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc sql_alloc with SQL_EXPR_AGGREGATE, name, args, distinct, 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Window function expression per SQL/Foundation 4.15 ("Window functions").
window_spec is a heap record describing PARTITION BY / ORDER BY / frame.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation
sql_alloc with SQL_EXPR_WINDOW_FUNCTION; p0 = function expression,
p1 = window_spec, p2 = filter expression (or 0).
@End Implementation
@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints
@Security_Scope
Owns all three.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "sql_window_function" takes function_expr as Integer, window_spec as Integer, filter_expr as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc sql_alloc with SQL_EXPR_WINDOW_FUNCTION, function_expr, window_spec, filter_expr, 0
End Process

@Reasoning
CASE WHEN expression per SQL/Foundation 6.12.  branches is a List of
two-entry sublists [condition_expr, result_expr]; else_expr is the
trailing ELSE or 0.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation
sql_alloc with SQL_EXPR_CASE_WHEN; p0 = branches list, p1 = else expr.
@End Implementation
@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints
@Security_Scope
Owns branches and else.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "sql_case_when" takes branches as Integer, else_expr as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc sql_alloc with SQL_EXPR_CASE_WHEN, branches, else_expr, 0, 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Subquery expression (scalar or EXISTS, depending on context).  payload
is a SELECT statement record.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation
sql_alloc with SQL_EXPR_SUBQUERY; p0 = SELECT statement pointer.
@End Implementation
@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints
@Security_Scope
Owns subquery.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "sql_subquery" takes select_stmt as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc sql_alloc with SQL_EXPR_SUBQUERY, select_stmt, 0, 0, 0
End Process

@Reasoning
CAST(expr AS type) expression per SQL/Foundation 6.13.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation
sql_alloc with SQL_EXPR_CAST; p0 = inner expression, p1 = target type name.
@End Implementation
@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints
@Security_Scope
Owns expr and type name.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "sql_cast" takes inner_expr as Integer, target_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc sql_alloc with SQL_EXPR_CAST, inner_expr, target_type, 0, 0
End Process

@Reasoning
COLLATE expression per SQL/Foundation 6.11.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation
sql_alloc with SQL_EXPR_COLLATE; p0 = inner expression, p1 = collation name.
@End Implementation
@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints
@Security_Scope
Owns expr and collation name.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "sql_collate" takes inner_expr as Integer, collation_name as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc sql_alloc with SQL_EXPR_COLLATE, inner_expr, collation_name, 0, 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SELECT STATEMENT
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Construct a SELECT statement record.

Payload slots:
  p0 = WITH clause (List of CTE records, or 0)
  p1 = select item list (required, non-zero)
  p2 = FROM tree (List of join-spec records, or 0)
  p3 = "rest" record holding WHERE/GROUP/HAVING/ORDER/LIMIT/OFFSET
       fields (allocated lazily by sql_select_set_*)
@End Reasoning
@Implementation
sql_alloc with SQL_STMT_SELECT.
@End Implementation
@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints
@Security_Scope
Owns all four payloads.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "sql_select" takes select_list as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc sql_alloc with SQL_STMT_SELECT, 0, select_list, 0, 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Attach an optional WITH clause (a List of CTE records) to a SELECT.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation
Write the cte_list pointer into payload 0.
@End Implementation
@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints
@Security_Scope
Null-safe.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "sql_select_set_with" takes select as Integer, cte_list as Integer returns Integer:
    If select is equal to 0:
        Return SQL_NULL
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with select, SQL_OFF_P0, cte_list
    Return SQL_OK
End Process

@Reasoning
Attach a FROM/JOIN tree to the SELECT.  from_list is a List of join-spec
records.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation
Write into payload 2.
@End Implementation
@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints
@Security_Scope
Null-safe.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "sql_select_set_from" takes select as Integer, from_list as Integer returns Integer:
    If select is equal to 0:
        Return SQL_NULL
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with select, SQL_OFF_P2, from_list
    Return SQL_OK
End Process

@Reasoning
The "rest" record holds WHERE/GROUP/HAVING/ORDER/LIMIT/OFFSET.  Size 64
bytes, layout:

  off  0  WHERE expression
  off  8  GROUP BY list (List of expressions)
  off 16  HAVING expression
  off 24  WINDOW clause list (List of named window specs)
  off 32  ORDER BY list (List of order-item records)
  off 40  LIMIT expression
  off 48  OFFSET expression
  off 56  reserved
@End Reasoning
@Implementation
Layout.allocate(64); zero all slots.
@End Implementation
@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints
@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on OOM.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "sql_select_rest_alloc" returns Integer:
    Let rec be proc allocate from Layout with 64
    If rec is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rec, 0, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rec, 8, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rec, 16, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rec, 24, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rec, 32, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rec, 40, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rec, 48, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rec, 56, 0
    Return rec
End Process

@Reasoning
Helper: ensure the rest-record exists on the SELECT.  Returns the rest
pointer.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation
If payload 3 is 0, allocate rest record and store it; return current
pointer.
@End Implementation
@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints
@Security_Scope
Null-safe.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "sql_select_ensure_rest" takes select as Integer returns Integer:
    If select is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let rest be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with select, SQL_OFF_P3
    If rest is equal to 0:
        Set rest to (proc sql_select_rest_alloc)
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with select, SQL_OFF_P3, rest
    End If
    Return rest
End Process

@Reasoning
Set the WHERE expression on a SELECT.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation
Ensure rest record; write WHERE slot.
@End Implementation
@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints
@Security_Scope
Null-safe.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "sql_select_set_where" takes select as Integer, where_expr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let rest be proc sql_select_ensure_rest with select
    If rest is equal to 0:
        Return SQL_NULL
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rest, 0, where_expr
    Return SQL_OK
End Process

Process called "sql_select_set_group_by" takes select as Integer, group_list as Integer returns Integer:
    Let rest be proc sql_select_ensure_rest with select
    If rest is equal to 0:
        Return SQL_NULL
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rest, 8, group_list
    Return SQL_OK
End Process

Process called "sql_select_set_having" takes select as Integer, having_expr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let rest be proc sql_select_ensure_rest with select
    If rest is equal to 0:
        Return SQL_NULL
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rest, 16, having_expr
    Return SQL_OK
End Process

Process called "sql_select_set_order_by" takes select as Integer, order_list as Integer returns Integer:
    Let rest be proc sql_select_ensure_rest with select
    If rest is equal to 0:
        Return SQL_NULL
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rest, 32, order_list
    Return SQL_OK
End Process

Process called "sql_select_set_limit" takes select as Integer, limit_expr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let rest be proc sql_select_ensure_rest with select
    If rest is equal to 0:
        Return SQL_NULL
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rest, 40, limit_expr
    Return SQL_OK
End Process

Process called "sql_select_set_offset" takes select as Integer, offset_expr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let rest be proc sql_select_ensure_rest with select
    If rest is equal to 0:
        Return SQL_NULL
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rest, 48, offset_expr
    Return SQL_OK
End Process

@Reasoning
Read accessor: WHERE expression (or 0 if none).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation
Load rest pointer, then load slot 0.
@End Implementation
@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints
@Security_Scope
Null-safe.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "sql_select_get_where" takes select as Integer returns Integer:
    If select is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let rest be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with select, SQL_OFF_P3
    If rest is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rest, 0
End Process

Process called "sql_select_get_group_by" takes select as Integer returns Integer:
    If select is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let rest be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with select, SQL_OFF_P3
    If rest is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rest, 8
End Process

Process called "sql_select_get_having" takes select as Integer returns Integer:
    If select is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let rest be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with select, SQL_OFF_P3
    If rest is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rest, 16
End Process

Process called "sql_select_get_order_by" takes select as Integer returns Integer:
    If select is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let rest be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with select, SQL_OFF_P3
    If rest is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rest, 32
End Process

Process called "sql_select_get_limit" takes select as Integer returns Integer:
    If select is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let rest be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with select, SQL_OFF_P3
    If rest is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rest, 40
End Process

Process called "sql_select_get_offset" takes select as Integer returns Integer:
    If select is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let rest be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with select, SQL_OFF_P3
    If rest is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rest, 48
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: INSERT / UPDATE / DELETE STATEMENTS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
INSERT statement per SQL/Foundation 14.11.

Payload slots:
  p0 = target table name
  p1 = column list (List of column-name strings, or 0 for "all columns")
  p2 = values: either a List of value-row lists (List of List of exprs)
       or a single SELECT statement; the discriminator is p3 (= 0 means
       values rows; = 1 means SELECT subquery).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation
sql_alloc with SQL_STMT_INSERT.
@End Implementation
@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints
@Security_Scope
Owns all four payloads.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "sql_insert_values" takes table as Integer, columns as Integer, rows as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc sql_alloc with SQL_STMT_INSERT, table, columns, rows, 0
End Process

Process called "sql_insert_select" takes table as Integer, columns as Integer, source_select as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc sql_alloc with SQL_STMT_INSERT, table, columns, source_select, 1
End Process

@Reasoning
UPDATE statement per SQL/Foundation 14.10.

Payload slots:
  p0 = target table
  p1 = assignment list (List of [column_name, expr] sublists)
  p2 = FROM tree (PostgreSQL-style multi-table UPDATE; 0 if plain UPDATE)
  p3 = WHERE expression (or 0)
@End Reasoning
@Implementation
sql_alloc with SQL_STMT_UPDATE.
@End Implementation
@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints
@Security_Scope
Owns all four payloads.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "sql_update" takes table as Integer, assignments as Integer, from_list as Integer, where_expr as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc sql_alloc with SQL_STMT_UPDATE, table, assignments, from_list, where_expr
End Process

@Reasoning
DELETE statement per SQL/Foundation 14.8.
Payload slots:
  p0 = target table
  p1 = USING list (PostgreSQL-style multi-table DELETE; 0 if plain)
  p2 = WHERE expression (or 0)
@End Reasoning
@Implementation
sql_alloc with SQL_STMT_DELETE.
@End Implementation
@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints
@Security_Scope
Owns payloads.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "sql_delete" takes table as Integer, using_list as Integer, where_expr as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc sql_alloc with SQL_STMT_DELETE, table, using_list, where_expr, 0
End Process

